{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_2hayden_ver02/data/sn83045462/00280604975/1949050901/0415.xml":{"full_text":"Washington's Kindergarten Blocks Go Modern\nKindergarten blocks are not\nwhat they used to be in the pub\nlic schools here.\nMo longer do blocks mean the\nlittle square objects children have\nbeen playing with for decades.\nWhen a kindergarten teacher talks\nabout blocks now she means large\n\"building blocks\" with which the\nfive-year-olds can build houses,\nbridges, boats and innumerable\nother things.\nThis type of large building\nblocks was introduced into a few\nkindergartens here in the city sev\neral years ago. Just last week\nschool officials ordered another\n$3,800 worth of them.\nBy the' end of this year, almost\ntall kindergartens will have the\nnew type.\nAt the Truesdell Elementary\nSchool, the kindergarten class of\n1 Mrs. Vesta Lynn is preparing for\nI a circus this week. Prom the\nblocks the boys and girls have\n(constructed cages for lions\u2014\neverybody wants to be the .lion\u2014\nand a cidbus tent.\nThe circus tent. Mrs. Lynn ad\nmits, is like children\u2019s art. It\n'needs some interpretation before\n\u2018an adult can see it. The cages\n[look like cages, however.\nA set of the blocks cost $150.\nBut they are permanent and will\nj last for years. The sets consist\nof long pieces of wood, wheels,\nI squares, angles, all eorts of shapes.\nMetal rods, which go through\nl holes already bored, hold what\never is built together.\nThe traditional small square\ni blocks are still used but they have\nfallen largely to the status of\n.toys\u2014not educational aids.\nMrs. Lu Verne Walker, kinder\ngarten and first grade supervisor,\nexplained that with these building\nblock sets, practically the entire\nkindergarten curriculum can be\ndramatised for the children.\nDramatic play is what the\nchildren need. They like to re\nlive the world about them, she\nAustralia's Top Red\n'Tells All/ Spurring\nDrive on Communists\nBy Fred B. Hubbard\nForeign Correspondent of The Star and\n\u2022he Chicago Daily Nows\nCANBERRA, Australia, May 9\nAustralia\u2019s half hearted fight\nagainst communism here has re\nceived a healthy shove forward\nfrom Cecil Sharpley, a Com\nmunist for 14 years.\nUntil recently a top Red leader\nin Victoria, Sharpley decided to\n\u201ctell all\u201d and he did pretty ef\nfectively in a series of newspaper\narticles.\nRestricted by Australia\u2019s rigid.*\nlibel l|$rs, Sharpley didn\u2019t quite:\nsucceed in \u201ctelling all.\u201d But hbr\ndisclosures of the inside workings\nof the Communist Party have\nunderlined the fact that the Reds\nare pretty well organized here.\nFor one thing, Sharpley\u2019s spe\ncific accounts of how Reds rigged\nunion elections and perpetrated\nvote frauds have come as a shock\nto rank-and-file unianists.\nUnion President Resigns.\nOne union president hu re\nsigned pending investigation of\nSharpley\u2019s claim that the official\nwas elected on s' Communist\nrigged vote.\nAnother development is that\nthe Victoria government plans to\nhold a royal commission investi\ngation into Red activities in that\nstgte.\nAnd It is clearly evident that\nthe opposition leaders will demand\nthat the federal government also\ninstitute a probe when Parlia\nment resumes. Reportedly, th*\nopposition has additional informa\ntion from Sharpley that can\u2019t be\nprinted.\nSharpley, woh says he <juit the\nparty because \u201cit is fiercely anti\nDemocratlc and wants a victor\nious Russian war,\u201d makes these\nsignificant points:\nAustralian Communists are out\nto weaken the country\u2019s defenses,\nretard industrial production, and\nlower workers\u2019 wages.\nCall Big Strikes.\nThey hope by weakening Aus\ntralia to thus weaken the British\nCommonwealth and Anglo-Amer\nican understanding. -j\nMost big strikes in Australia\nover the past three years have\nbeen called and run by Com\nmunists.\nOpposition parties, which have\nlong demanded outlawing the\nReds in Australia, find themselves\nin an embarrassing position after\nfiharpley\u2019s revelations. Fat the\nex-Communist says ban of this\nnature'would have little effect\u2014\nthat the party already has \u201ccom\nplete and thorough\" plans to go\nunderground.\nHis advice to those fighting Red\nactivities is to conduct union elec\ntions under strict supervirion, take\nfirm action against industrial\nlaw violations by Reds, and pro\nvide for inspection of the Com-,\nmunist Party\u2019s balance sheets and\nmembership lists.\nCows Repulse Leopard\nAfter Attack on Calves\nJ. Webster told in Chipinga,\nSouthern Rhodesia, how two of his\ncows fought desperately to save\ntheir calves from a leopard.\nAfter badlv mauling the calves,\nths leopard was driven off by the\ncows and ran into the bush. Web\nster, running up in time, wounded\nthe animal and it rushed at him.\nHis dogs intervened and the leop\nard took to a tree, where it was\nkilled.\nThose cages and pens in the picture were built by the 5-year-olds in a kindergarten class\nat Truesdell Elementary School from the kindergarten \u201cblocks\u201d that have replaced the tradi\ntional little squares, shown at right. Left to right are Kathleen Boyle, 834 Gallatin street N.W\nTonl-Margaret Francis, 408 Ingraham street N.W.; George Hughes, 6111 Hamilton street N.W.;\nJoseph Galvagne, 700 Longfellow street N.W.; Bobby Fickley, 511 Longfellow street N.W. (making\nlike a lion in the cage), and Meredith Hansel, 414 Jeffrt'son street N.W. \u2014Star Staff Photo.\nsaid. From the blocks they learn\nto play together and get social\nvalues. The physical co-ordina\ntion and the thinking that is in\nvolved teaches them to solve prob\nlems.\nEven language studies are\nhelped by the blocks, Mrs. Walker\nsaid. The children learn to com\nmunicate their ideas as they build,\ni For instance, in the circus being\nplanned at the Tinesdell kinder\ngarten the children learn lots of\nnew words. They delve into fas\ncinating fields never opened to\nthem before. They learn all about\nlions, tigers, elephants.\nWhen they build a boat, for in\nstance, the whole field of trans\nportation is open. The next\nproject then may be a train.\nAll of the dozens and dozens of\nobjects which the children can\nbuild from the large blocks appear\nrealistic. The boys and girls can\nget behind the counter of a grocery\nstore they construct. They can\nsit in the circus tent or get in the\ncage.\nIn fact, the problem now at\nTruesdell is how to keep them out\nof the cages. Everybody really\nwants to be a lion. Mrs. Lynn said.\nFree Reich Elections\nHeld Basic Problem\nAt Ministers' Parley\nBy David M. Nkhol\nForeign Correspondent of The Star and\ntha Chicago Daily News\nBERLIN, May 8.\u2014The question\nof free elections throughout Ger\nmany is emerging as the core of\nthe problem facing the Four\nPower Foreign Ministers once the\nBerlin blockade is lifted next\nThursday.\nFrom the standpoint of the\nWestern Allies it would be Im\npossible to agree to establishment\nof a unified or federalixed Ger\nmany on any other basis than a\ngeneral ballot for all Germany.\nFrom the Soviet standpoint, on\nthe other hand, such elections in\nthe country\u2019s present temper prob\nably would mean virtual disap\npearance of the Communist-con\ntrolled Socialist Unity Party as a\nparty of any political importance.\nCommunist strength in the West\nBerlin elections last December\nwas, estimated ft less than .V per\ncent. That proportion probably\nis about the same in Western Ger\nmany.\nPlebiscite Planned.\nEastern German leaders, aware\nof their predicament, are pushing\n<9lans for a plebiscite May 15 and\n16 which will be a rubber stamp\n\u2018'ja\" for handpicked delegates to\nthe third \"people\u2019s congress.\u201d\nFor bargaining purposes at least\nthe Soviets probably will propose\nthis agency as a constitutional\nconvention for the future German\nstate.\nWestern leaders, on the other\nhand, are moving rapidly for thei\nfirst time toward completion of a\nWestern German constitution and;\nestablishment of a Western Ger-i\nman state. In this they have the\nfull support of the three western\nAllies.\nThe way would remain open for\nadmission of the provinces of\nEastern Germany, but this would\nrequire considerable changes in\nthe social, political and economic\nstructure which the Soviets have\ninstalled over four years and would I\nbe reluctant to see go by the\nboards.\nBerlin Airlift Evaluated.\nMeanwnile. experts are begin\nning to count up some of the\nachievements of the Berlin airlift.\nIn point of immediate result, of'\ncourse, it has kept the city free,\nand it has checked the Soviet pro\ngram for bringing the whole of\nGermany under Soviet influence.\nOn a longer-range basis there are\nmany who believe that it has\neither prevented World War HI\nor shoved it back a considerable\nnumber of years.\nBut there is another aspect\nwhich has been more or less over\nshadowed by the drama of the!\npolitical arena. By and large, the\nairlift has wiped out almost all\nformer concepts about movements\nby air of bulk supplies for civilian\nor military purposes.\nThe 10 xh months of the airlift\nhave furnished the sternest prov\ning ground ever devised for the!\naircrews themselves and for al-j\nmost everything connected with;\ncargo aircraft. The greatest ad-j\nvances have been made in actual\ntraffic patterns in the air and in;\nsystems of controlling these from\nthe ground by means of radio\nand radar.\nVery little of this communica\ntions equipment was designed\nspecifically' for the airlift job. It\nwas already in existence and has\nin some instances been much im\nproved. What is new is the use\nto which it has been placed.\nPlane Design Modified.\nSo far as lift flyers are con\ncerned some arguments which are\nstill raging in the United States\nhave been settled long ago. No>\nexperienced pilot on the Berlin\nrun would trade ground-controlled\napproach (OCA) for the instru\nment-landing system <ILS> which\nmost commercial flyers at home\nstill seem to prefer.\nModifications in aircraft design\nas a result of the lift operation\nwill be many but unspectacular.\nWhat has been proved beyond any\n[question is the economy of ever\nlarger airplanes, provided air\nfields can be equipped to handle\nthem.\nMore impressive has been the\ndevelopment of maintenance pro\ncedures. Spare parts manuals have\nbeen completely revised.\nIn addition it has- been dis\ncovered that basically sound air\ncraft. which the C-54 certainly is,\ncan be rebuilt every 1,000 hours\nfor almost perpetual operation.\nSome pilots say they improve.\nEvery phase of cargo handling\nhas been altered from the moment\nsupplies leave the mines or fields\nor factories to the actual loading\nand unloading of aircraft.\nSuperior to anyone of these in\ndividual achievements, however, is\nthe whole system itself. Tech\nniques and equipment have been\nso perfected they can be picked\nup bodily and set down almost\nany place they might be required.\nMoscow Puppet Ploy\nSatirizes Hollywood\nSy rtw Ausciattd Prm\nMOSCOW.\u2014The Moscow Pup\npet Theater has staged a \u201csatin'\non Hollywood.\u201d It is called \u201cUnder\nthe Rustle of Tour Eyelashes.\u201d\nThe play is supposedly based on\na Hollywood version of Carmen.\nThis Carmen is a secret agent\nof Moscow. The production carries\nher through automobile races, falls\nfrom cliffs and a large amount of\nlove making and kissing.\n\u201cThe play,\u201d a reviewer wrote in\n\u201cEvening Moscow,\u201d \u2018.\u2018brings to light\nthe American movie directors who\ncan be bought and act under the\ndirection of the reactionaries.\u201d\nWillard Thorp to Speak\nWillard L. Thorp, assistant Sec\nretary of State for Economic Af\nfairs, will address the annual lun\ncheon of the Columbia University\nClub of Washington at 12:30 pm.\nMay 21 in the 8horeham Hotel.\nU. S. Businessmen\nIn Shanghai to Try\nWorking Under Reds\n>y Au\u00abci\u00ab\u00ab\u00ab4 VrMt\nSHANGHAI, May American\nbusinessmen in Shanghai see\nlittle future under a Communist\niregime. But most of them intend\nto stay and give it a try.\nThey hope they will be permit\nted to operate under Red control\nand that conditions may Improve,\nparticularly the money situation.\nAll are trying to figure out how\nto convince the Communists they\nhave something to offer China.\nThey expect a serious business\nslump when the Reds first arrive,\nbut hope for a revival after things\nget shaken down.\nAmericans own nearly $12d,000.\n000 worth of property in Shanghai.\nThis is nearly 80 per cent of\nAmerican holdings in all China.\nCaban Trade Greater.\nOne American businessman said\nthis \"sounds like a lot, but really\nit\u2019s only peanuts. American trade\nwith Cuba is greater than with\nChina.\u201d\nAmerican exports to China in\n194? ran 8353.000.000; Cuba took\n8500,000,000.\nAmerican Investments in China\nare only about one-seventh of\nthose of the British.\nThe biggest American compa\nnies here are Standard Vacuum\nOil. Texas Oil (China), American\nExpress, Pan American Airways,\nNorthwest Airlines, American\nPresident Lines, Chase Bank, the\nNational City Bank, the Shanghai\nPower Co. and the Shanghai Tele\nphone Co.\nThere also is a great deal of\nmissionary property churches,\nschools and compounds.\n202 U. S. Firms Own Property.\nAltogether there are 202 Ameri\ncan firms and organizations own\ning property. 88 of these are cor\nporations. The number has de\nclined steadily as war conditions\nbecame worse. One year ago there\nwere 252 American firms.\nAmerican businessmen in pon\ndering their future noted that one\nAmerican-owned bank was forced\nto close in Tientsin when the\nReds took over. Another bank,\nalthough it continued to operate,\nwas not recognised by the new\nregime.\nBefore any foreign firms could\ndo much business under the Reds\na foreign exchange would have\nto be established. This hasn't\nbeen done by the Communists in\nNorth China. Instead, trade has\nbeen on a barter basis like in the\nold clipper ship days of a cen\ntury ago.\nSEWING MACHINES\n_..\ns#\nNow\n\nFREE HOME DEMONSTRATION\nJ-YEAR SERVICE GUARANTEE MW MOTOR NEW CONTROL\nNEW SIW-LITI NEW AIRPLANE LUGGAGE CARRYING CASE\nClean-Rite Vacuum Store\n92$ F Stmt N W. MEtropoliton 5600\nOp\u2014 f N A FX. (TfcrMey \u2014tiI JO MA.)\nFlyer end Nurse Safe\nAfter 6-Day Hike Back\nFrom Canadian Crash\nBy George Brimmed\nVANCOUVER. British Columbia\nMay <Distributed by Associated\nPress*.\u2014Sunburned and grimy,\nweary of chocolate bars and mos\nquitoes. Bill Grant and Sheila\nCure came home last night\u2014six\ndays overdue.\nDressed in the asms light cloth\ning they wore when U:eir small\nairplane crashed late last Monday\nin a driving snowstorm stop S OtO\nfoot Mount Hosomcen. 135 miles\neast, they told this story:\nMr. Grant. 30, a Vancouver pi\nlot. and the 29-year-old rtudent\nnurse left Cranbrook, B. C.. en\nroute to Vancouver at am. Mon\nday.\n\"The weather was fine.\u201d Mr.\nGrant said.\n\"We hit the first bad weather\nwhen we tried to go through the\nCoquihalla Pass. It was coming\ndown like curtains.\"\nWings Aec am slated lee.\nThey tried the Big Bend high\nway route then, but had to turn\nback. They tried to get to *Jrince\nton, B. C.. \"but we were blocked\nIn solid.\u201d\n\"We were about at the border\nwhen it really closed in.\u201d Mr\nGrant said.\n\"Then she started to ice up\nThe wings and struts were iced\nand the prop was. too.\n\"I knew that was it. I started\nto ease down slowly and the next\nthing I saw was snow and trees.\n\"I shouted to Sheila: 1 Watch It.\nHere we go!\nMr. Gram said one wing hit a\nsnag going in and the propeller\nsnapped off. The only Injury\nsuffered was a bruised finger for\nMr. Grant.\nThe pair spent that night j\nunder freezing conditions\u2014in the\nhole dug by the nose of the plane\nwhen It crashed. \"It was awfully\ncold,\" said Miss Cure. \"Bitter.\u201d\nStarted Trek Down Mountain.\nThe next morning \"we gathered\nwhat stuff we could and started\ndown the mountain.\u201d\nWith them they carried a com\npass. heavy clothing, a chart, the\naircrafts log book, all the paper\nthey could find and a pair of\ndrapes Sheila's mother had made\nifor the girl's room at Vancouver\nGeneral Hospital, where she Is a\nstudent nurse.\nMr. Grant was dressed in a\ntweed jacket, shirt and tie, light\ntrousers and heavy rubber boots.\nMiss Cure wore a sweater, her\nhospital blazer, grey slacks, and\nrubber mucklucks. All the food\nthey had was five chocolate bars.\nTheir first hazard appeared to\nbe an ice field. As they began to\ncross it. the field moved.\nThe pair was carried 500 feet.\n\"Sheila's head and one foot was'\nsticking out the top when it\nstopped.\" Mr. Grant said. Neither\niwas hurt.\n\"We realized we\u2019d have to ration\nour food.\" Miss Cure said. \"80\nwe had only one square of choco\ni late apiece each day. Of course\ni we had lots of water. The river\n[ran all along the bottom of the\ngorge.\u201d\nMr. Grant\u2014who doesn't smoke\u2014\ncarried one booklet of matches.\nAnd with an old newspaper they\nlit tires each night.\nThey slept on ledges near the\nbottom of the valley wearing all\nthe clothes they had and wrapped\nin Miss Cure's homespun curtains.\nBy Thursday they were \"feeling\npretty low.\u201d\nAbout noon, they saw two Royal\n[Canadian Air Force planes.\n\"That was the first indication\nwe had they were looking for us.\"\nMr. Grant said. \u201cIt really bucked\n\u2019us up. We tried to signal them\u2014\nwe built a fire\u2014but they were too\nfar away.\u201d\nFriday they saw more planes\nand that afternoon two RCAF\nDakotas dropped the three para\nrescue men who later guided them\nto safety. \"A helicopter dropped\nus a radio and \u2018K\u2019 rations. That\nwas the first real food we'd had\nsince Monday.\u201d Mr. Grant said.\nSaturday morning they met the\npara-rescue men. \u201cWere we glad\nto see them!\u201d\nLater, the ground party which\ncame 11 miles from a lumber\ncamp Joined them. They were\nguided to the camp, where a\nUnited States Coast Guard heli\ncopter picked them up for the air\njourney to Vancouver.\nb\u00ab ivrt\nto too..*\nJOHN B. KINNIDY?\nV&me fame**\"\nIll* facts sk*wt Hi*\ngr*ot*st tfawc* fa\n\u2022if fact kittoryi\nTh\u00bb NCW^NEW\nNext Meek\nT*or mfate #\u2014far\nwtW lnwr* It\nAallWrtoci Factory Dealer\nfar Williams OH-O-Matia\nColoiial Fiel Oil\n1700 ia Salaa tt U.\nML 110\nVANCOUVER. BRITISH COLUMBIA \u2014SAFE AFTER DATS IN WILDS\u2014Bill Orant ttemd from\nleftt and Sheila Cure, who wandered six days in the Canadian-American border wiMt after\ntheir plane crashed, talk with their rescuers while eating at a logging camp\nAP WMrephoto from the Coast Ouacd\nAngry Tribesmen Quit\nBritish Colony Over\nKilling of Stray Cow\nBy Ernie Hill\nCwrreiBow^i TH# %*mr\nCh\u00ab\u00ab9\u00ab 0\u00abity N#wt\nSIN, Gambia. May An esti\nmated 1.000 Fula tribesmen and\ntheir families are movmi across\nthe border of this British colony\nto pastures in Benegalese French\nWest Africa.\nAll because a cow was shot.\nA tribe of nomadic cattlemen,\nthe Fulas are angry over what\nthey call \"a travesty of British\njustice.\"\nThe cow was shot while being\ntaken to market along with 20\nother cows It strayed, entered\ngovernment property where it\nstopped the bullet of an over\nzealous native guard. Two calves\nwere seized but later, released.\nBesides the migration of angry\nnatives the incident has led to an\ninvestigation accompanied by a\nseries of blasts and counterblasts\nin Gambia newspapers.\nChanting Time* Cited.\n\"The sense of British justice\nhas been raised to such a high\ndegree in Gambia.\" declares one\nwriter jn a Gambit newspaper\n\u201cthat the accidental death of one\ncow creates a storm.\n\"There were times on the Afri\ncan coast when the death of 30\nPula slaves would cause km ex\ncitement. Our Pula friends should\nstop and realise that British jus\ntice gives them every right to air\ntheir grievances.\"\nFulas say they have not forgot\nCameras\nBOUGHT\u2014 SOLD\nRENTED RETAINED\nSOMMERS \u25a0XCHANM I\n1419 NCW VOIK AVL Mi. 9*9>\nECZEMA ITCH\nOof yoo down? fry\nRESINOL\nOINTMENT\nhr long-lotting rolltf\nten the black pages of history\nwhen slave-running was the big\ngest business on this sultry African\ncoast. They claim that is no eg*\ncuse for killing a tribesmen s cow\nThis village named Sin is up\nthe Gambia River on the British\nFrench border. Most of the town\nis on the French side The shoot\ning of the cow occurred 10 mile*\nfrom here In the village of Baa.*\non the river.\nRiver Is \"Highway.**\nThe trip up the river is made In\na motorboat The river curve*\nthrough swamp lands Gambia*\nthousands of acres of pesnuis are\nplanted on both sides since the\nliver la virtually the only way to\nyet them to Bathurst\nSin Includes about 100 native\nhuts. It is an Important rest spot\nfor nomadic cattlemen bringing\nherds to the river for shipment\nto the ocean.\nJang Kalaf. a tribal leader, has\nlodged an official protest with\nGambia governor general. In a\nletter to lhe Gambia Outlook he\nwrite*\n\"It ahould be aueeeed that ah\nof u\u00bb Fula* can eaatlv migrate to\nthe French whet* our kith and\nktn ore enjoying fteednm Migra\ntion of three-fourth* of the Man\naatang Fula* and eventual tr*na\nff r of other Fula Tillage*\nneighboring temtorte* wtll de\npopulate the Fulladu da\u00bbt and\naubnequenlly cauae financial Voag\nto Gambia W# want jutttee\nPoles Report 20% Boost\nIn Tobocco Production\nIt ItmwM\nWARSAW Poland Poland \u2022to\nbacco far tone* reported they ex\nceeded by 3(t per cent their pro\nduction lartet for the fleet quarter\nof IMS\nA total of 4 734 l\u00bbl ooo algae*\nrite* without mouthpiece* and\n130 730.000 with mouthpiece* were\nproduced Other tobacco product*\nincluded 4 474 000 cigar* approgl\nmately 400 000 pound* of pipe to\nbacco and 40 000 pound* of anuff.\nFactory Sale\nTABLE PADS\n9Q.95 v.\nW! ALSO RCCOVIR rn VI T\nTOUR OLO PADS 11\nar